  <slides>

    <slide id="1">
      <content>
        <text>Topic: Partial Derivatives</text>
        <text>Given the function:</text>
        <math>f(x, y) = x^2 + 2y^2 + 2</math>
        <question>
          <text>What is the partial derivative of f with respect to y?</text>
          <answers>
            <answer index="1">4y</answer>
            <answer index="2">2x</answer>
            <answer index="3">2y</answer>
            <answer index="4">4x</answer>
          </answers>
          <correctAnswer>1</correctAnswer>
          <explanation>Treating x as constant: d/dy (2y^2) = 4y. The x^2 and +2 terms vanish. So df/dy = 4y.</explanation>
        </question>
      </content>
    </slide>

    <slide id="2">
      <content>
        <text>Topic: Partial Derivatives</text>
        <text>Given the function:</text>
        <math>f(x, y) = x^2 + 2y^2 + 2</math>
        <question>
          <text>What is the partial derivative of f with respect to x?</text>
          <answers>
            <answer index="1">4y</answer>
            <answer index="2">2x</answer>
            <answer index="3">2y</answer>
            <answer index="4">4x</answer>
          </answers>
          <correctAnswer>2</correctAnswer>
          <explanation>Treating y as constant: d/dx (x^2) = 2x. The 2y^2 and +2 terms vanish. So df/dx = 2x.</explanation>
        </question>
      </content>
    </slide>

  </slides>
</learningContent>
